Analysing European Crop Production Trends with FAOSTAT Dataset

Abstract

This notebook investigates agricultural trends in Europe from 19612023 by analyzing FAOSTAT data for 144 different crops. After loading and cleaning separate CSV files for harvested area, production, and yield, we merge them into a single table. Because plotting 144 individual crops overwhelms most visualizations, a generative-AI mapping groups crops into 13 broad categories (e.g., Cereals, Fruits, Vegetables, etc.). We then explore total production, area harvested, and yield at both the individual-crop and category levels, employing pie charts, bar charts (including log-scaled versions), heatmaps, treemaps, and, finally, a country-level animated choropleth. At each step, we highlight the strengths of each graphicwhat it reveals about European agricultureand discuss its limitations (why it can be misleading, cluttered, or insufficient). The goal is to demonstrate a reproducible, critique-driven visualization workflow that surfaces both macro- and micro-level insights into Europes crop production patterns over six decades.

Here lie all the imports needed across this exploration

So as we needed to download the data in 3 separate files (due to site limitations) we want to have all the variable in one place for more easier use, so we are gonna load the 3 datasets, merge them and then clean some of the null values.

#Load each CSV separately
df_area = pd.read_csv('FAOSTAT_data_en_5-31-2025-harvest-area.csv')
df_prod = pd.read_csv('FAOSTAT_data_en_5-31-2025-production.csv')
df_yld  = pd.read_csv('FAOSTAT_data_en_5-31-2025-yield.csv')

#Inspect columns to identify the common keys (including 'Unit')
print("Area-harvest columns:", df_area.columns.tolist())
print("Production   columns:", df_prod.columns.tolist())
print("Yield        columns:", df_yld.columns.tolist())

#Reduce each DataFrame to the key columns 
df_area_trim = (
    df_area
    .loc[:, ['Area', 'Item', 'Year', 'Value', 'Unit']]
    .rename(columns={
        'Value': 'Area_harvested',
        'Unit':  'Unit_Area_harvested'
    })
)

df_prod_trim = (
    df_prod
    .loc[:, ['Area', 'Item', 'Year', 'Value', 'Unit']]
    .rename(columns={
        'Value': 'Production',
        'Unit':  'Unit_Production'
    })
)

df_yld_trim = (
    df_yld
    .loc[:, ['Area', 'Item', 'Year', 'Value', 'Unit']]
    .rename(columns={
        'Value': 'Yield',
        'Unit':  'Unit_Yield'
    })
)

#Merge the three DataFrames on the common keys: ['Area','Item','Year']
#outer merge so no data is lost if one file is missing a combination.
df_merge1 = pd.merge(
    df_area_trim,
    df_prod_trim,
    on=['Area', 'Item', 'Year'],
    how='outer'
)

df_merged = pd.merge(
    df_merge1,
    df_yld_trim,
    on=['Area', 'Item', 'Year'],
    how='outer'
)

#Check the result structure
print("Merged shape:", df_merged.shape)
print(df_merged.sample(10))

#Drop rows where all three metrics are NaN
df_merged = df_merged.dropna(subset=['Area_harvested', 'Production', 'Yield'], how='all')

#Inspect how many non-null entries exist, and confirm units
print("\nNon-null counts after merging:")
print(df_merged[['Area_harvested', 'Production', 'Yield']].notna().sum())

print("\nUnique units for each metric:")
print(" Area harvested units:", df_merged['Unit_Area_harvested'].unique())
print(" Production units:   ", df_merged['Unit_Production'].unique())
print(" Yield units:        ", df_merged['Unit_Yield'].unique())

Why This Helps

  • Clarity of data provenance:
    Loading and merging all three CSVs into a single df_merged ensures that for every row, you know exactly which country (Area), which crop (Item), and which year the measurement applies to, along with its area, production, and yield.

  • Preserves all available data:
    Using how='outer' prevents accidental loss of rows when one CSV might be missing a particular countrycropyear combination.

  • Uniform column naming:
    By renaming Value Area_harvested/Production/Yield and Unit Unit_XXX, it becomes immediately clear which column holds which measurement.

Limitations

  • Large intermediate DataFrame: After merging, the DataFrame has over 150k rows and nine columns (plus indices), which can be memory-heavy and slow to manipulate.

  • Possible mismatched units: We drop rows if all three metrics are NaN, but rows where only one or two metrics are present remain. This can introduce confusing partial recordsfor example, a crop might have Production but missing Area_harvested,

In[6]:
# Because we have multiple years and countries and we are currently looking at total production of the crops we need to agreggate the data in such way that we have item and production
production_per_item = (
    df_merged
    .groupby('Item')['Production']
    .sum()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
)

#To compute total production by Group without altering df_merged, create a temporary DataFrame:
df_temp = df_merged.copy()
df_temp['Group'] = df_temp['Item'].map(crop_to_group)

production_by_group = (
    df_temp
    .groupby('Group')['Production']
    .sum()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
)

# Pie chart of all 144 crop items
fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))

# Generate 144 distinct colors from a colormap
colors_items = plt.cm.tab20b(np.linspace(0, 1, len(production_per_item)))

wedges1, texts1, autotexts1 = ax1.pie(
    production_per_item.values,
    labels=production_per_item.index,
    autopct='%1.1f%%',
    colors=colors_items,
    startangle=90,
    wedgeprops=dict(edgecolor='white', linewidth=0.5)
)

# Make labels very small because there are 144 slices
for txt in texts1:
    txt.set_fontsize(4)
for atxt in autotexts1:
    atxt.set_fontsize(3)

ax1.set_title('Total Production by Crop Item (all 144)', fontsize=14, pad=20)
plt.tight_layout()


#Pie chart of grouped categories, with legend (no onslice labels)
fig2, ax2 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 12))

groups = production_by_group.index
values = production_by_group.values

# Compute percentages for each group
total = values.sum()
percentages = values / total * 100
legend_labels = [f"{grp}: {p:.3f}%" for grp, p in zip(groups, percentages)]

# Use a discrete colormap with at least len(groups) distinct colors
cmap = plt.get_cmap('tab20')
colors_groups = cmap.colors[: len(groups)]

# Create the pie WITHOUT onslice labels or percentages
wedges2, _ = ax2.pie(
    values,
    labels=None,       
    startangle=90,
    colors=colors_groups,
    wedgeprops=dict(edgecolor='white', linewidth=1)
)

# Add a white circle for donut style
centre_circle = plt.Circle((0, 0), 0.45, color='white', linewidth=0)
ax2.add_artist(centre_circle)

# Title
ax2.set_title('Total Production by Category (grouped)', fontsize=16, pad=20)

# Add legend on the right with category names + percentages
ax2.legend(
    wedges2,
    legend_labels,
    title="Category  % of Total",
    loc="center left",
    bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0, 0.3, 1),   # Positions legend to the right of the pie
    fontsize=10,
    title_fontsize=12
)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Why This Helps

  • (A) 144slice pie demonstrates the long tail:
    A handful of top crops (e.g., Wheat, Maize, Barley) account for most production, while the other ~140 combined are small. Seeing 144 tiny slices drives home how fragmented raw data is.

  • (B) 13slice grouped pie immediately clarifies:
    Cereals alone might contribute 6070% of total European production, followed by Sugar Crops, Roots & Tubers, etc. The legend avoids label crowding on the wedges.

Limitations

  • (A) Unreadable detail:
    Even with very small font (size 4), a 144slice pie is nearly impossible to read. Tiny slivers overlap or become invisible entirely. Its a valid demonstration of why one cannot visualize raw items in a pie.

  • (B) Piechart distortions:
    Pie charts hide small categories, since small percentage differences (e.g., 1.2% vs. 1.8%) are hard to compare by angle. Also, with 13 slices, minor categories crowd the legend and require precise reading of the legend text.

  • No time dimension:
    These pies collapse 19612023 into a single aggregate; they cannot show temporal trends.

#Aggregate total Area_Harvested by Item
area_per_item = (
    df_merged
    .groupby('Item')['Area_harvested']
    .sum()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
)

#Aggregate total Area_Harvested by Group (using a temporary copy)
df_temp_area = df_merged.copy()
df_temp_area['Group'] = df_temp_area['Item'].map(crop_to_group)
area_by_group = (
    df_temp_area
    .groupby('Group')['Area_harvested']
    .sum()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
)

#Plot: Pie of all 144 Items by Area_Harvested
figB1, axB1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))
colors_items_B = plt.cm.tab20b(np.linspace(0, 1, len(area_per_item)))
wedgesB1, textsB1, autotextsB1 = axB1.pie(
    area_per_item.values,
    labels=area_per_item.index,
    autopct='%1.1f%%',
    colors=colors_items_B,
    startangle=90,
    wedgeprops=dict(edgecolor='white', linewidth=0.5)
)
for txt in textsB1:
    txt.set_fontsize(4)
for atxt in autotextsB1:
    atxt.set_fontsize(3)
axB1.set_title('Total Area Harvested by Crop Item (all 144)', fontsize=14, pad=20)
plt.tight_layout()

#Plot: Pie of Groups by Area_Harvested (legend on right)
figB2, axB2 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))
groups_B = area_by_group.index
values_B = area_by_group.values
total_B = values_B.sum()

Now that we have established that given the number of crops in our dataset we kind of have to group them i have chose to create a new version of the dataset in which we utilise these new categories and the only major difference being the mapping of Item to a Group (with appropraite aggregation of the Production Area harvested and Yield values)

#Copy df_merged so the original remains unchanged
df_temp = df_merged.copy()

#Add the 'Group' column by mapping each 'Item' to its category
df_temp['Group'] = df_temp['Item'].map(crop_to_group)

#Define a helper to pick the first non-null value in a series
def first_non_null(series):
    non_null = series.dropna()
    return non_null.iloc[0] if not non_null.empty else np.nan

#Group by both 'Group' and 'Year' to retain year information
df_grouped = (
    df_temp
    .groupby(['Group', 'Year'])
    .agg({
        'Area_harvested':       'sum',
        'Unit_Area_harvested':  first_non_null,
        'Production':           'sum',
        'Unit_Production':      first_non_null,
        'Yield':                'sum',
        'Unit_Yield':           first_non_null
    })
    .reset_index()
)

#To display large numbers without scientific notation:
pd.set_option('display.float_format', '{:,.0f}'.format)

Why This Helps

  • (A) Linear version:
    Directly shows absolute totals for each metric by category, making it obvious that Cereals dwarf every other group in terms of total production (e.g., hundreds of millions of tonnes) and area (tens of millions of hectares).

  • (B) Logscale version:
    Corrects for extreme magnitude differenceson a linear axis, smaller categories (e.g., Spices & Aromatics yield) might appear as a flat line at zero. The log scale pulls up small values so you can compare relative differences across all 13 categories, whether they produce 10 tonnes or 10 tonnes.

Limitations

  • Linear version hides small bars:
    On a linear yaxis, categories like Industrial Crops (total production < 10,000 t) are invisible next to Cereals (hundreds of millions).

  • Log scale may confuse readers:
    Not everyone is familiar with log scales. Vertical distances no longer correspond to additive differences (e.g., a bar at 10 vs. 10 looks the same distance as 10 vs. 10), so one must read the axis labels carefully.

  • Loss of yearbyyear detail:
    Both versions collapse six decades of data into one number per category, so any temporal trend is lost.

# Determine nonzero minima for log scaling
area_min = pivot_area[pivot_area > 0].min().min()
prod_min = pivot_production[pivot_production > 0].min().min()

Why These Heatmaps Help

  • Compact Temporal Overview (Linear + Log):
    By pivoting df_grouped into a (13 ~63) gridrows = crop Group, columns = Year each heatmap shows year-by-year values in a single view. You can instantly see, for instance, that Cereals occupy the largest area almost throughout the 1960s1980s and then decline gradually after 1990, or that Fruits yield steadily climbs from the 1970s onward.

  • Linear vs. Log Scales Reveal Different Patterns:

    • Linear Area Heatmap: Because Area Harvested ranges from a few thousand hectares (e.g., Industrial Crops) up to nearly 200 million ha (Cereals), the linear version lets you see absolute changes in big categories: the bright yellow of Cereals is unmistakable.
    • Log-Scaled Production & Yield Heatmaps: Production and Yield also span multiple orders of magnitudefrom a few hundred tonnes/ha up to hundreds of millions. Using LogNorm stretches out those small cells so that tiny rows (e.g., Industrial Crops) become visible, whereas on a linear color scale theyd be nearly black the entire time.

  • Row-Consistent Comparisons:
    All 13 categories share the same color mapping, so you can compare across rows. For example, you see whether Vegetables heat band in 2020 is hotter (higher) than Pulses/Legumes in 2010. With log normalization, a change from 10 t 10 t is the same vertical color shift as 10 t 10 t, making multiplicative (10) changes equally perceptible for large and small groups.

long_df = (
    df_merged
    .melt(
        id_vars=['Area', 'Year'],
        value_vars=['Production', 'Area_harvested', 'Yield'],
        var_name='Metric',
        value_name='Value'
    )
    .dropna(subset=['Value'])
)

# helper that tries M49 numeric lookup first, then falls back to namebased lookup
def m49_or_name_to_iso3(area_value):
    # Convert to string, strip whitespace
    s = str(area_value).strip()
    
    #If its purely digits (M49), try numeric lookup
    if s.isdigit():
        try:
            country = pycountry.countries.get(numeric=s.zfill(3))
            return country.alpha_3
        except (KeyError, AttributeError):
            return None
    
    #Otherwise, attempt namelookup (case/aliasinsensitive)
    try:
        return pycountry.countries.lookup(s).alpha_3
    except (LookupError, AttributeError):
        return None

long_df['iso_alpha'] = long_df['Area'].apply(m49_or_name_to_iso3)

#Identify unmapped FAOSTAT areas once (for reference)
missing_iso = long_df.loc[long_df['iso_alpha'].isna(), 'Area'].unique()
if len(missing_iso) > 0:
    print("Unmapped FAOSTAT areas (will be dropped or overridden):", missing_iso)

#Manual overrides for known FAOSTAT areas/aliases that still cannot resolve
#(for example, M49 codes for USSR might never map; or historical names)
manual_overrides = {
    "810": None,  # Yugoslavia might be code 810
    "738": None,  # USSR
    "748": None,  # Czechoslovakia
    "Belgium-Luxembourg": None,
    "Netherlands (Kingdom of the)": "NLD",
    "Serbia and Montenegro": None,
    "Yugoslav SFR": None
}

#Apply overrides only to rows where iso_alpha is still None
mask_missing = long_df['iso_alpha'].isna()
long_df.loc[mask_missing, 'iso_alpha'] = long_df.loc[mask_missing, 'Area'].map(manual_overrides)

# Drop any remaining rows that still lack an ISO code
long_df = long_df.dropna(subset=['iso_alpha'])

for metric_name, title, color_label in [
        ("Production",     "Crop Production by Country over Time (Europe, 19612023)",     "Production (t)"),
        ("Area_harvested", "Crop Area Harvested by Country over Time (Europe, 19612023)", "Area Harvested (ha)"),
        ("Yield",          "Crop Yield by Country over Time (Europe, 19612023)",          "Yield (kg/ha)")
    ]:

    #Filter to just this metric
    df_metric = long_df[long_df['Metric'] == metric_name].copy()
    
    #Group by (Area, Year, iso_alpha) & sum the values
    country_year = (
        df_metric
        .groupby(['Area', 'Year', 'iso_alpha'], as_index=False)['Value']
        .sum()
    )
    
    #Create the animated choropleth
    fig = px.choropleth(
        country_year,
        locations="iso_alpha",
        color="Value",
        hover_name="Area",
        animation_frame="Year",
        range_color=[country_year["Value"].min(), country_year["Value"].max()],
        color_continuous_scale="Viridis",
        title=title,
        scope="europe"
    )
    
    # Adjust layout (size, remove frame)
    fig.update_layout(
        width=1200,
        height=800,
        geo=dict(showframe=False, showcoastlines=True),
        title_x=0.5
    )
    
    # Update colorbar label
    fig.update_coloraxes(colorbar_title=color_label)
    
    # Render as HTML in the notebook
    html_str = fig.to_html(include_plotlyjs="cdn")
    display(HTML(html_str))

 'Serbia and Montenegro' 'USSR' 'Yugoslav SFR']

Why This Helps

  • Geographic context: Instead of focusing on Groups, we now shift to Countries. An animated choropleth shows, for instance, how French production evolves from 1961 to 2023, then Germany, Italy, etc., in visual succession.

  • Temporal dynamics: The slider lets you step year by year, revealing events like the expansion of wheat production in Eastern Europe after 1990 or the gradual rise of olive production in Southern Europe.

  • Interactive exploration: Hovering over a country reveals exact numbers for that year. This interactivity is far more engaging than a static map or table.

Limitations

  • Requires internet for Plotly JS: Embedding via to_html(include_plotlyjs="cdn") means that viewing the HTML needs a working internet connection to fetch Plotlys JavaScript library.

  • Mismatches in country names: Despite manual overrides, some FAOSTAT country names (e.g., Czechoslovakia) cant map cleanly to ISO3 codes. Those rows get dropped, leaving historical gaps.

  • No subregional nuance: Europe as a scope lumps Eastern, Western, and Northern Europe together. One might miss differences in, say, Scandinavian vs. Mediterranean yield trends unless you manually zoom in.
